article.description:
Reserve guard Elena Baranova had 19 points,
seven rebounds and three assists Thursday night as the New York
Liberty rallied from an early 20-point deficit and beat the
Washington Mystics 65-60.
article.headline: Baranova has all-around effort in win
article.linkText: Liberty bounce back from early deficit to edge Mystics
article.story:
WASHINGTON (AP) -- Reserve guard Elena Baranova had 19 points,
seven rebounds and three assists Thursday night as the New York
Liberty rallied from an early 20-point deficit and beat the
Washington Mystics 65-60.

Baranova replaced Vickie Johnson, who sprained her right ankle
with 14:54 remaining in the first half and did not return.

Chamique Holdsclaw led the Mystics with 21 points, seven
rebounds and five assists.

Tamika Whitmore scored 13 for New York, and Crystal Robinson and
Kristen Sharp each added 10.

New York (16-16) made its largest comeback in franchise history
and moved into a tie with Cleveland and a half-game ahead of
Connecticut for the last two spots in the Eastern Conference.

"Obviously, no one gives people anything, you've got to take
it," New York coach Richie Adubato said. "We have a rivalry, and
I think they (Mystics) would have enjoyed their season by knocking
us out of the playoffs."

Washington (9-23) jumped out to a 10-0 lead as the Liberty
missed their first six shots. Holdsclaw and Muriel Page each scored
four points in the run.

Helen Luz's two 3-pointers and another by Coco Miller helped the
Mystics build a 23-4 lead with 8:18 remaining in the half and were
up by as much as 30-10 before the Liberty pulled within 33-19 at
halftime.

Trailing 54-43 with 8:28 left in the second half, the Liberty
needed little more than four minutes to pull within 56-55 behind
3-pointers by Baranova, Sharp and Linda Frohlich and a jumper by
Whitmore.

Washington's Asjha Jones and Stacey Dales-Schuman sandwiched
buckets around Tari Phillips' missed layup to give the Mystics a
60-54 lead with 2:48 left.

The Liberty answered with an 8-0 run, capped by Whitmore's layup
for a 62-60 lead with 40.1 seconds left. Sharp added two free
throws and Phillips one in the final 29 seconds to seal the
comeback.

"We really wanted to upset New York," Dales-Schuman said.
"Our goal was to disturb what other teams are trying to do since
we don't have a chance to play in the playoffs."

The Liberty threatened to match a franchise-low 15 points in the
first half until Baranova's 3-pointer with 36 seconds left. She
finished with 19 points on 7-for-10 shooting, including 5-for-6
from 3-point range.

Baranova scored 11 first-half points, including three
3-pointers.
